===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|sewen}}, {{m|enm|seowen}}, {{m|enm|sowen}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|sīwian}}, {{m|ang|sēowian}}, {{m|ang|sēowan||to sew, mend, patch, knit together, link, unite}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*siwjaną||to sew}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*sīw-||to sew}}, {{m|ine-pro|*syuh₁-}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|sew||to sew}}, {{cog|frr|saie}}, {{m|frr|sei||to sew}}, {{cog|stq|säie||to sew}}, Danish {{m|da|sy}}, Polish {{m|pl|szyć}}, Russian {{m|ru|шить}}, Swedish {{m|sv|sy}}, {{cog|la|suō}}, {{cog|sa|सीव्यति}}. Related to {{l|en|seam}}.

====Pronunciation====
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/səʊ/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/soʊ/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-sew.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|əʊ|lang=en}}
* Homophones: [[so]], [[soh]], [[sow]] {{qualifier|sense 2}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb|sews|sewing|sewed|sewn|past_ptc2=sewed|past_ptc3=sewen|past_ptc3_qual=obsolete}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To use a [[needle]] to pass [[thread]] repeatedly through (pieces of [[fabric]]) in order to join them together.
#: ''Balls were first made of grass or leaves held together by strings, and later of pieces of animal skin '''sewn''' together and stuffed with feathers or hay.''
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To use a [[needle]] to pass [[thread]] repeatedly through pieces of [[fabric]] in order to join them together.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To enclose by sewing.
#: ''to '''sew''' money into a bag''

